{
  "domain_id": "abstract-algebra",
  "domain_name": "Abstract Algebra",
  "id_prefix": "math.abst",
  "level_range": [
    4,
    7
  ],
  "description": "The study of algebraic structures \u2014 groups, rings, fields, modules, and algebras \u2014 defined by abstract axioms. Unifies and generalizes arithmetic, geometry, and symmetry via a common algebraic framework.",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "id": "math.abst.algebraic-structure",
      "name": "Algebraic Structure",
      "aliases": [
        "algebraic system"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.found.axiom",
        "math.found.set-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.group-theory",
        "math.abst.ring-theory"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "A set together with one or more binary operations satisfying axioms. The same set with different operations yields different structures. Abstract algebra studies these structures independently of the nature of elements.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 2,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.85,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, Ch.1; Herstein, Topics in Algebra"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.binary-operation",
      "name": "Binary Operation",
      "aliases": [
        "operation",
        "closed operation"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.found.function-set-theoretic"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "A function *: S\u00d7S\u2192S assigning a unique element to each ordered pair. Closure: the result always stays in S. Associativity, commutativity, identity, and inverses are additional properties an operation may have.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 2,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a71.1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-theory",
      "name": "Group",
      "aliases": [
        "group axioms"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [
        "math.abst.subgroup",
        "math.abst.cyclic-group",
        "math.abst.group-homomorphism"
      ],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.binary-operation"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.subgroup",
        "math.abst.coset"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [
        "math.linalg.vector-addition"
      ],
      "description": "A set G with binary operation \u00b7 satisfying: closure, associativity, identity element e (ge=eg=g), and inverses (\u2200g, \u2203g\u207b\u00b9: gg\u207b\u00b9=e). Abelian (commutative) group: additionally gh=hg. Examples: (\u2124,+), (GL_n(\u211d),\u00b7).",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 5,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, Ch.1; Herstein, Topics in Algebra, Ch.2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-operation",
      "name": "Group Operation Examples",
      "aliases": [
        "group table",
        "Cayley table"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [
        "math.linalg.vector-addition"
      ],
      "description": "Concrete groups: (\u2124\u2099,+) cyclic; (\u2124\u2099*,\u00b7) units mod n; symmetric group S\u2099 (permutations); dihedral group D_n (symmetries of n-gon); GL_n (invertible matrices). Cayley table fully describes a finite group.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.85,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a71.3\u20131.5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.subgroup",
      "name": "Subgroup",
      "aliases": [
        "subgroup criterion"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.coset",
        "math.abst.normal-subgroup"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "H\u2264G iff H is non-empty, closed under the operation, and closed under inverses (subgroup criterion). Equivalently: \u2200a,b\u2208H, ab\u207b\u00b9\u2208H. Trivial subgroups: {e} and G itself.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a72.1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.cyclic-group",
      "name": "Cyclic Group",
      "aliases": [
        "cyclic",
        "generator",
        "\u27e8g\u27e9"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [
        "math.abst.group-order"
      ],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "G = \u27e8g\u27e9 = {g\u207f : n\u2208\u2124}; generated by a single element g. Finite cyclic of order n: \u2124\u2099\u2245\u27e8g\u27e9. Every subgroup of a cyclic group is cyclic. The cyclic groups are the simplest non-trivial groups.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a72.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-order",
      "name": "Order of Group and Elements",
      "aliases": [
        "order of a group",
        "order of an element"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.lagrange-theorem"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "|G| = number of elements in G. ord(g) = smallest positive n with g\u207f=e. In finite group: ord(g) divides |G| (Lagrange). Order 1 only for identity; cyclic subgroup \u27e8g\u27e9 has order ord(g).",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 3,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a72.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.coset",
      "name": "Coset",
      "aliases": [
        "left coset",
        "right coset",
        "aH"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.subgroup"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.lagrange-theorem",
        "math.abst.normal-subgroup"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "Left coset of H in G: aH = {ah : h\u2208H}. Cosets partition G; all cosets have the same size |H|. aH=bH iff a\u207b\u00b9b\u2208H. Index [G:H] = |G|/|H| = number of distinct cosets.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.lagrange-theorem",
      "name": "Lagrange's Theorem",
      "aliases": [
        "Lagrange theorem for groups"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.coset"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "If G is finite and H\u2264G, then |H| divides |G|. Equivalently, [G:H]\u00b7|H|=|G|. Corollary: ord(g) divides |G|; groups of prime order are cyclic.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 3,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.normal-subgroup",
      "name": "Normal Subgroup",
      "aliases": [
        "normal",
        "N\u25c1G",
        "invariant subgroup"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.coset"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.quotient-group"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "N\u25c1G iff gNg\u207b\u00b9=N for all g\u2208G, equivalently gN=Ng (left and right cosets coincide). Kernels of homomorphisms are always normal. Normal subgroups are exactly those for which the quotient group is well-defined.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.quotient-group",
      "name": "Quotient Group",
      "aliases": [
        "factor group",
        "G/N"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.normal-subgroup"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.first-isomorphism-theorem"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "G/N = {gN : g\u2208G} with operation (aN)(bN)=abN. Well-defined iff N\u25c1G. |G/N|=[G:N]=|G|/|N| (finite case). The quotient 'collapses' N to the identity.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.85,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-homomorphism",
      "name": "Group Homomorphism",
      "aliases": [
        "group map",
        "\u03c6:G\u2192H"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [
        "math.abst.group-isomorphism"
      ],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.group-isomorphism",
        "math.abst.first-isomorphism-theorem"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [
        "math.linalg.linear-map"
      ],
      "description": "A map \u03c6:G\u2192H with \u03c6(ab)=\u03c6(a)\u03c6(b). Preserves group structure. ker(\u03c6) = {g\u2208G : \u03c6(g)=eH} is a normal subgroup of G. im(\u03c6) is a subgroup of H.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.9,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a71.6"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-isomorphism",
      "name": "Group Isomorphism",
      "aliases": [
        "isomorphic groups",
        "G\u2245H"
      ],
      "parent": "math.abst.group-homomorphism",
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-homomorphism"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "A bijective homomorphism \u03c6:G\u2192H. Isomorphic groups are structurally identical. Automorphism: isomorphism G\u2192G. Classify groups up to isomorphism: cyclic groups \u2124\u2099; abelian groups as products of cyclic groups.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "analyze",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.85,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a71.6"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.first-isomorphism-theorem",
      "name": "First Isomorphism Theorem",
      "aliases": [
        "fundamental theorem of homomorphisms"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.quotient-group",
        "math.abst.group-homomorphism"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.second-isomorphism-theorem"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "If \u03c6:G\u2192H is a homomorphism, then G/ker(\u03c6) \u2245 im(\u03c6). The quotient by the kernel is isomorphic to the image. Generalizes to rings and modules. Proved by showing the induced map \u1e20\u2192im(\u03c6) is an isomorphism.",
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "understand",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.85,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.second-isomorphism-theorem",
      "name": "Second and Third Isomorphism Theorems",
      "aliases": [
        "diamond isomorphism theorem",
        "lattice isomorphism theorem"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.first-isomorphism-theorem"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "Second (Diamond): If H\u2264G and N\u25c1G, then HN/N \u2245 H/(H\u2229N). Third: If N\u25c1H\u25c1G, then (G/N)/(H/N) \u2245 G/H. Together with the first theorem, they describe the subgroup lattice structure under homomorphisms.",
      "difficulty": "expert",
      "estimated_hours": 4,
      "bloom": "analyze",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.8,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a73.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.group-action",
      "name": "Group Action",
      "aliases": [
        "G-set",
        "orbit",
        "stabilizer"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [
        "math.abst.burnside-lemma",
        "math.abst.sylow-theorems"
      ],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-theory",
        "math.found.function-set-theoretic"
      ],
      "unlocks": [
        "math.abst.sylow-theorems"
      ],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "A group action of G on set X: a map G\u00d7X\u2192X satisfying identity and compatibility. Orbit of x: Gx={gx:g\u2208G}. Stabilizer of x: G\u2093={g:gx=x}. Orbit-Stabilizer theorem: |Gx|\u00b7|G\u2093|=|G|.",
      "difficulty": "expert",
      "estimated_hours": 6,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.8,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, Ch.4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.burnside-lemma",
      "name": "Burnside's Lemma",
      "aliases": [
        "Burnside's counting theorem",
        "Cauchy-Frobenius lemma"
      ],
      "parent": "math.abst.group-action",
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-action"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "Number of distinct orbits = (1/|G|)\u2211_{g\u2208G}|X^g| where X^g is the set fixed by g. Counts distinct colorings/patterns under symmetry. Key tool in combinatorial enumeration (Polya counting).",
      "difficulty": "expert",
      "estimated_hours": 5,
      "bloom": "apply",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.75,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a74.3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.sylow-theorems",
      "name": "Sylow Theorems",
      "aliases": [
        "Sylow p-subgroup",
        "Sylow's theorem"
      ],
      "parent": null,
      "children": [],
      "requires": [
        "math.abst.group-action",
        "math.nt.prime-number"
      ],
      "unlocks": [],
      "related": [],
      "cross_links": [],
      "description": "For |G|=p\u1d50\u00b7k (p prime, p\u2224k): (1) Sylow p-subgroups of order p\u1d50 exist; (2) they are all conjugate; (3) their number n\u209a satisfies n\u209a|k and n\u209a\u22611(mod p). Used to classify groups of given order.",
      "difficulty": "expert",
      "estimated_hours": 7,
      "bloom": "analyze",
      "mastery_threshold": 0.75,
      "references": [
        "Dummit & Foote, Abstract Algebra, \u00a74.5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "math.abst.symmetric-group",
      "name": "Symmetric Group",
      "aliases": [
